posts.text:
What is the reason for making it so hard to recover profiles and allowing for immediate access to your account.
The reason why I had to even go through some sort of verification was ridiculous to begin with. I didn't even forget the password.
I was on a business trip to HK and had to log in to Gmail. I guess Gmail knew there was an attempt to login from an "unusual" location, so it asked me questions and i may have possibly failed or i may have passed it but still it asked for phone numbers to send verification code... Do you not think that it is likely that i would not be able to take texts whilst i am abroad?
In any case, I seemed to have been locked out of the account because I couldn't verify that I was the owner of the account even though i didn't forget my password.
Anyways, now having to reset the passwords, it takes 3-5 workings days?? Come on, what's the point of emails these days. We send and receive important docs via email. Might as well revert to faxing the way you are treating importance of emails.
Very fed up.
Luckily i have the account logged in on my phone so just getting by but you need to get better. Security is very very important but if you are going to be an @ss about it then provide some real support.

thread.title: Correlation of sociodemographic and clinical parameters with depression and distress in patients with hematologic malignancies
thread.title_full: Correlation of sociodemographic and clinical parameters with depression and distress in patients with hematologic malignancies

posts.author: Αλέξανδρος Σφακιανάκης (noreply@blogger.com)
posts.title: Correlation of sociodemographic and clinical parameters with depression and distress in patients with hematologic malignancies
posts.text:
Abstract A quarter of cancer patients struggle with distress or depression during their illness. Multiple organizations including the National Comprehensive Cancer Network recommend universal screening for distress and depression. Herein, we describe a universal screening program in patients with hematologic malignancies and factors associated with distress and depression. Between December 2013 and February 2015, patients with hematologic malignancies took the Patient Health Questionnaire 9 (PHQ-9) and Distress Thermometer (DT) prior to receiving their first outpatient parenteral chemotherapy. Patient demographic information as well as information regarding visit burden and baseline use of psychiatric medications were recorded. A PHQ-9 score of ≥ 9 and a DT score ≥ 4 suggested a high risk of major depression and distress. Intergroup comparisons of categorical and continuous variables were performed via chi-square and Wilcoxon rank-sum tests. Multivariate models were constructed using the stepwise selection technique using all potential variables. Two hundred forty-six patients with a median age at diagnosis 65 years (range 18–94 years) were included. In the multivariate analysis, a PHQ-9 score ≥ 9 was associated with living alone ( P  = 0.007), positive PHQ-2 ( P  = 0.003), and high Charlson comorbidity index (CCI; P  = 0.02), while a DT score ≥ 4 was associated with being married ( P  = 0.03) and female ( P  = 0.03). There was no other association with high scores on either questionnaire. Patients with hematologic malignancies often have prolonged treatment and surveillance. We identified subpopulations within this group who may be at high risk of developing distress and depression and who should be aggressively screened even when universal screening programs are not available.

posts.author: Anonymous
posts.text:
>>80175713
+/- measures "how well your team does when you are on the court"
It's measured by the point differential when you're on the court. If you're on the court for only 1 minute of play, and in that minute the other team goes on a 10-0 run, then that would mean you had a -10. Inversely, if your team went on a 10-0 run, then you would have a +10.
It's an extremely meme stat that ignores a shitload of factors that skew it.

posts.author: Yankun Wang
posts.title: Sensors, Vol. 17, Pages 2828: Indoors Locality Positioning Using Cognitive Distances and Directions
posts.text:
Sensors 2017 , 17 (12), 2828; doi:10.3390/s17122828 (registering DOI) Indoors Locality Positioning Using Cognitive Distances and Directions , Hong Fan 1,2, * and Ruizhi Chen 1,2 1 State Key Lab for Information Engineering in Surveying, Mapping and Remote Sensing, Wuhan University, 129 Luoyu Road, Wuhan 430079, China 2 Collaborative Innovation Center of Geospatial Technology, Wuhan University, Wuhan 430079, China * Author to whom correspondence should be addressed. Received: 17 October 2017 / Revised: 2 December 2017 / Accepted: 2 December 2017 / Published: 7 December 2017 (This article belongs to the Section Physical Sensors ) No Abstract Spatial relationships are crucial to spatial knowledge representation, such as positioning localities. However, minimal attention has been devoted to positioning localities indoors with locality description. Distance and direction relations are generally used when positioning localities, namely, translating descriptive localities into spatially explicit ones. We propose a joint probability function to model locality distribution to address the uncertainty of positioning localities. The joint probability function consists of distance and relative direction membership functions. We propose definitions and restrictions for the use of the joint probability function to make the locality distribution highly practical. We also evaluate the performance of our approach through indoor experiments. Test results demonstrate that a positioning accuracy of 3.5 m can be achieved with the semantically derived spatial relationships. View Full-Text ► ▼ Figures
